@node "SprWidth" "Width"

                                @{b}Width@{ub}

Select a sprite width for your purpose here. Choose between 16, 32, or
64  pixels.  Keep  in  mind  that sprites wider than 16 pixels are not
supported prior to AGA.
@endnode

@node "SprCtrl" "Control Words"

                            @{b}Control Words@{ub}

Sprite  datalists  for  hardware-proramming  purposes  require control
words  at  their  beginning.  These  control  words  contain   all the
information  needed  for  the  sprite  display, such as horizontal and
vertical  start  positions, vertical stop position, and the attach-bit
mentioned in the @{" colors " link "SprCols" 0} section.

ART-Pro supports sprite control words in four ways: None, Empty, Auto,
or Prompt. Use the cycle gadget to adjust one of these.


@{u}None@{uu}     ART-Pro doesn't care about control words. They will be
         omitted.
         

@{u}Empty@{uu}    ART-Pro includes control words at the beginning of the
         sprite datalists, but they're empty, i.e. set to zero.


@{u}Auto@{uu}     ART-Pro includes sprite control words containing ALL the
         information needed for proper display. The control word
         calculation will be performed as follows:

VerticalStart     = raster line $2c + brush's top edge inside your
                    picture

VerticalStop      = raster line $2c + brush's top edge + brush's
                    height

HorizontalStart   = DMA start $80 + brush's left edge inside your
                    picture


@{u}Prompt@{uu}    ART-Pro will bring up a requester for a customized control
          word calculation when saving one or multiple sprites.
          Here you can adjust the VerticalStart and HorizontalStart
          values as well as the image-relative brush coordinates.


The latter two settings can be extremely useful for you, if you're one
of  those  hardware  programmers  who  use  static sprites for complex
screen  layouts.  Experienced  programmers  will have noticed that the
values  used  with  the  "Auto" setting apply to standard non-overscan
screens. Use the Prompt setting if these don't fulfill your needs.
@endnode

@node "FuturePlans" "Future Plans"

                            @{b} Future plans@{ub}

This  is  just a list of features that may become part of ART-Pro some
day. Don't blame me if you can't find your favourite ideas realized in
the next release. Better you get in contact with  @{" me " link "Author" 0} in order to lay
stress  upon  features  listed  herein,  or  to   propose   your   own
suggestions.


                                @{u}Savers@{uu}

         STENCIL MASK           mask generated with a specific
                                set of colors

         GIF                    popular format
                        
         BMP                    PC format



                                @{u}Loaders@{uu}

         DATATYPE               universal loader using system
                                datatypes

         GIF                    popular format
         
         BMP                    PC format



                           @{u}Brush operators@{uu}

         MULTICUT               allowing multiple brushs to be
                                cut and to be linked either
                                vertically or horizontally



                           @{u}Image operators@{uu}

         SCALE                  flexible image scaling

         MIX                    to mix two images with variable
                                transparency



                          @{u}Palette operators@{uu}

         PALETTE                RGB/HSV palette adjustments
         
         PACK COLORS            to remove unused colors and
                                to re-order the palette

         LESS COLORS            to reduce the number of colors
                                used by an image

         MATCH WITH IMAGE       for the current image using the
                                palette of another image

         SHARE WITH IMAGE       for different images using the
                                same palette, with optimized usage
                                of all colors for both images
                                
         
         

                            @{u}Miscellaneous@{uu}

         font-sensitive GUI     to run on public screen or workbench

         HAM-brushes            for brushes in HAM6 or HAM8 are not
                                always treated correctly in ART-Pro's
                                current release

         Mempool management     avoiding memory fragmentation using
                                a private memory pool

         ANIM support

         ARexx port
         


Some of these features are currently being worked at. Nevertheless, it
depends  on  YOUR feedback what ideas will be implemented first (or at
all).
@endnode

@node "History" "History"

                               @{b} History@{ub}


@{b}V0.79@{ub}  26.1.1995 (major bugfix)

        - Parts of the guide have been rewritten for V0.78. Some
          passages were linked incorrectly, some were completely
          wrong, some were malformatted. Fixed.

        - Saving images which have been loaded as RAW HAM6 crashed.
          Fixed.

        - Displaying or saving images which have been loaded as RAW
          EHB could crash under certain circumstances. In addition
          to that, saving images which have been loaded as RAW-EHB
          led to 64color non-EHB images. Fixed.

        - Iconify plus un-iconify "un-registered" ART-Pro. Solved.

        - The Load-RAW screenmode requester will now keep the last
          selected screenmode.

        - The RGB-CHUNKY-12Bit and RGB-CHUNKY-24Bit savers crashed
          on 68000 and 68010 based machines. This has been fixed.
          Now the code differenciates correctly between 68000 and
          680x0 based machines for the use of optimized routines.

        - Minor bugs and several Enforcer-hits removed.


@{b}V0.78@{ub}  30.12.1994 (The Party 4 release)

        - After cutting a brush and iconifying, ART-Pro saved the
          complete picture instead of the brush. Solved.

        - GUI layout in the preference section changed, for the
          source code settings are now global and apply to all
          output formats.
        
        - RAW-CHUNKY (LEFT/RIGHT) savers implemented.
        
        - RGB-CHUNKY-12BIT and 24BIT savers implemented.

        - COLOR-RAW and COLOR-IFF loaders implemented.

        - First public release with a keyfile for registered users.

        - Ask Mask-Color crashed sometimes. Fixed.

        - User prompt for customized control-word calculation
          included to the sprite output settings. (Registered
          users only.)
        
        - various minor bugs fixed.


@{b}V0.77 ... V0.70@{ub}  (several internal releases)

        - Screenmode lock implemented. (Registered users only)
        
        - ART-Pro crashed when saving an 8bit copperlist as binary.
          This has been fixed.        

        - Source-generator completed. ART-Pro now supports
          Assembler, C, Basic, E, and Pascal.


@{b}V0.641@{ub} 12.11.1994  (quick update)

        - ART-Pro crashed on 68000 based machines - now fixed

        - ART-Pro did strange nosense when having no directory name
          in the file requester! Oops...


@{b}V0.64@{ub}  05.11.1994  (Coma Party Köln)

        - removed a major bug - ART-Pro crashed on exit if a
          screenmode wasn't available/supported - now fixed

        - bug in AutoCut fixed - left box edge not set correctly
          sometimes

        - added a text field at the control screen and inside
          the main window, displaying a brush's width in words 

        - ART-Pro now saves the selected loader/saver modules
          to its default prefs path on exit

        - now a busy-pointer appears when needed

        - some minor bugfixes


@{b}V0.62@{ub}  21.10.1994

        - added link-object

        - ART-Pro now saves its load/save paths to its default
          prefs paths on exit

        - some bugfixes


@{b}V0.60@{ub}  08.10.1994

        First puplic release for the tool competition at
        the Doomsday Party.
@endnode

@node "link" "Specify Linkdata"

                         @{b}Specify Link-Object@{ub}

After selecting @{" Save " link "Save" 0} and specifying a filename, a requester will pop
up  and  prompt  you  to  configure the link-object. The string gadget
entitled  "External  definition"  allows  you  to  define  a label for
external reference. Using the cycle button labelled "Memory Type", you
can  adjust  the  memory  type  for the object to be linked to. Choose
between  any,  chip,  or  fast.  Select  "Save"  or press its keyboard
equivalent  "s"  to  save  the  link-object  or  choose   "Cancel" for
abortion.
@endnode

@node "Lock" "Lock"

                                 @{b}Lock@{ub}

Using  this  checkmark  button,  you  can lock the screen mode that is
currently  being  selected.  Whenever  you load another image, ART-Pro
will try to keep the screen mode that you've adjusted before.

This feature is reserved for @{u}registered users only@{uu}.
@endnode

@node "COLORRAW" "COLOR-RAW"

                              @{b}COLOR-RAW@{ub}

This  loader allows you to load a raw palette over a previously loaded
image.  The  raw  color  data  will  be  interpreted according to your
preferred  @{" color  settings " link "Color_Format" 0}.  Remember,  the palette format cannot be
identified  automatically.  Don't blame ART-Pro if you find your image
colors scrambled after you've loaded a palette in a false format.

By  the  way,  it  makes few sense to load a raw palette @{u}before@{uu} you've
loaded an image.
@endnode

@node "COLORIFF" "COLORIFF"

                              @{b}COLOR-IFF@{ub}

With  this loader you can load an IFF palette to be used for the image
currently  being  loaded.  By  the  way,  it makes few sense to load a
palette @{u}before@{uu} you've loaded an image.
@endnode

@node "RAWCHLEFT" "RAW CHUNKY LEFT"

                           @{b}RAW-CHUNKY-LEFT@{ub}

This saver will generate chunky output, with the bits corresponding to
their bitplanes adjusted to the left. Have a look at this scheme:

                      chunky byte:    %12345678

Each digit represents its corresponding bitplane. RAW-CHUNKY-LEFT is a
rather  unconventional  format,  mainly  used   for   extremely   fast
chunky-to-bitplane  conversion  with the ADDX opcode. With this format
there's  no  need  to  shift  the  chunkies  when  having  less than 8
bitplanes.

See also the @{" RAW-CHUNKY-RIGHT " link "RAWCHRIGHT" 0} section.
@endnode

@node "RAWCHRIGHT" "RAW CHUNKY RIGHT"

                           @{b}RAW-CHUNKY-RIGHT@{ub}

This saver will generate chunky output, with the bits corresponding to
their bitplanes adjusted to the right. Have a look at this scheme:

                      chunky byte:    %87654321

Each  digit represents its corresponding bitplane. RAW-CHUNKY-RIGHT is
the  more common chunky format. Refer to @{" RAW-CHUNKY-LEFT " link "RAWCHLEFT" 0} for further
information.
@endnode

@node "RGB12" "RGB-CHUNKY-12BIT"

                          @{b} RGB-CHUNKY-12BIT@{ub}

We've  got  you demo coders here, haven't we? This saver will generate
truecolor  12Bit  output, with each pixel represented by a word in the
format  $0RGB.  Pictures  and  brushes  in  HAM6  and HAM8 are treated
correctly, of course.
@endnode

@node "RGB24" "RGB-CHUNKY-24BIT"

                          @{b} RGB-CHUNKY-24BIT@{ub}

This  saver  will  generate  truecolor  24Bit  output, with each pixel
represented  by  a  longword  in  the  format  $00RRGGBB. Pictures and
brushes in HAM6 and HAM8 are treated correctly, of course.
@endnode

@node "PalOp" "Palette Operation"

                          @{b}Palette Operation@{ub}

Right  now,  there's only one palette operator implemented to ART-Pro.
For that reason the palette operation selector appears ghosted in this
release.

                            @{" Color-Bias " link "ColorBias" 0}
@endnode

@node "ColorBias" "ColorBias"

                              @{b}Color Bias@{ub}

Color-Bias  is a great tool for global palette adjustments. Select the
color-bias  palette operator to enter your current picture with a tiny
control screen at its bottom.

This  control  screen  contains  six  sliders, entitled Color, Bright,
Contrast,  and  R/G/B. In addition to these, you find three buttons at
the right hand, entitled Use, Keep, Cancel.

Moving  a slider to the left will reduce the appropriate value, moving
it  to  the  right  will  increase it. Check it out to see the effect,
that's  much  easier than trying to explain this in a trivial way. The
Color-Bias palette modification will be performed real-time. This is a
great means for fine-tuning your palette.

Press  the  "Use" button or press its keyboard equivalent "U" to leave
this  section with the new palette. If you select "Cancel" or "C", you
abort  the  Color-Bias operator and undo all changes. Select "Keep" or
press  "K"  to  re-adjust  the  slider  knobs to zero with the current
settings.

By the way, color-biassing on HAM pictures won't do a good job in this
release of ART-Pro, for the rendering routines are not yet completed.
@endnode

@node "Width" "Width"

                                @{b}Width@{ub}

Use  this  cycle  gadget  to  adjust your preferred data width for the
source code generation. Choose between bytes, words, and longwords.
@endnode

@node "Features" "Features"

                          @{b}Brief feature list@{ub}

               (new V0.7x features appear @{b}highlighted@{ub})



    @{u}Comfortable GUI@{uu}
    
        * All functions driven by gadgets or keyboard equivalents
        * No menus on screens with weird resolutions and colors
        * Lots of options and settings for your individual taste
        * Comfortable brush cutting controlled on a seperate screen

    @{u}Highly flexible source code generation@{uu}

        * Generates Assembler, @{b}C, Pascal, E, and Basic@{ub} source
        * Handles variable indenting with tabs or spaces
        * Output may be bytes, words, or longwords

    @{u}Image conversion@{uu}

        * Handles IFF to RAW as well as RAW to IFF
        * Supports interleaved blitter formats
        * Outputs as IFF, source, binary, or link-object
        * Includes additional blitter words for shifted blitting
        * Automatically saves the colors associated with an image
        *@{b} Handles 12bit and 24bit truecolor output@{ub}

    @{u}Extensive sprite support@{uu}

        * Handles sprites in either 4 or 16 colors
        * Handles sprites being 16 / 32 / 64 pixels wide
        * Outputs as source, binary, or link-object
        * Allows you to cut several sprites in a single go
        * Automatically calculates sprites' control words
          according to their screen positions
        * @{b}User-customized control word calculation@{ub}

    @{u}Color functions@{uu}

        * Supports LoadRGB, pure, and copperlist formats
        * Generates AGA copperlists
        * Handles 4 and 32 bit color depths for LoadRGB
        * Outputs as IFF, source, binary, or link-object
        * @{b}Handles palette import as RAW and IFF@{ub}
        * @{b}Color-bias lets you control an image's saturation,
          contrast, brightness, and R/G/B in real-time@{ub}

    @{u}Masking functions@{uu}

        * Generates brush masks for either interleaved
          or noninterleaved blitting
        * Supports specific mask colors
@endnode

@node "Important" "Very important note to all users!"

                   @{b}Very important note to all users@{ub}

We plan to release ART-Pro's next major update with a lot of important
new  features.  We do not only want to introduce external modules, the
long-awaited  palette tool and the font-sensitive GUI, we also plan to
implement  the first image processing and rendering modules. (See also
the @{" future plans " link "FuturePlans" 0} section.)

However, rendering functions require well-equipped systems with higher
CPU  performance and a lot of memory. For that reason we would like to
know  if ART-Pro may demand an 68020 CPU. That means in detail that we
wouldn't  like to differenciate between 68000 and 68020 (and up) based
systems  -  we  would  rather  like to use 68020 (and up) code all the
time.  The  consequence  would  be  that  ART-Pro's   image processing
features won't be able to work on 68000 based systems.

The rendering routines are almost finished and quite fast yet, but the
speed could be enhanced even further with pure 68020 code. For ART-Pro
is  written  in  assembler,  it's  not  possible  to  simply turn on a
compiler  switch  in  order to produce an 68020 version. In fact, it's
almost  twice  the work if you have to differenciate between 68000 and
68020  processors  for any single routine.

Making  sophisticated  use  of the 68020 abilities, on the other hand,
leads to blazingly fast routines: Some tests on an A3000 do a complete
rendering  cycle  from HAM6 to truecolor and back to HAM6 in less than
two  seconds  for a 320x256 imagery. It would be silly work to support
all  processors  if there are no or very few users who've got an 68000
based  system  still.  Another  point is that we can do more truecolor
processing  with pure integer arithmetics on an 68020, where we had to
pass  certain  mathematical  tasks to the operating system's libraries
for 68000 compatibility.

We  guess  that  most  users of ART-Pro are programmers right now, and
some  new  users  will  do  image processing as well. Typically, these
people have got well-equipped systems.

Once  again,  we need YOUR ideas, suggestions and criticism, no matter
if  you're  registered  or  not. First of all, we want to make ART-Pro
suit YOUR needs. So don't hesitate to @{" send an E-Mail or a letter " link "Author" 0} and
write a few lines.
@endnode

